Ingress controllers, the proxies that do the work.

Here is a crucial distinction. The ingress object is just a piece of configuration sitting in the ay-pee-eye server. By itself it does nothing. You also need an ingress controller, an actual running proxy that reads ingress objects and implements the routing.

Several controllers exist. They all read the same ingress format, but each implements it differently. The most deployed is ingress n-ginx, a community project that runs n-ginx and reloads it on change. Traefik is popular for development, with auto discovery and a nice dashboard. There are performance focused ones built on haproxy. On the clouds, there are controllers that provision a real cloud load balancer per ingress. And the service mesh flavoured ones are built on envoy.

The rule is, you pick one ingress controller per cluster, install it, typically with helm, and then write ingress resources that target it.

That targeting is done through the ingress class. A cluster can actually run more than one controller, say an internal only one and a public one. Each controller registers an ingress class resource. And each ingress picks its controller by setting the ingress class name field. So the flow is, install a controller, which registers a class, and then every ingress names the class it wants. Without a controller installed, your ingress objects are inert. They are a to do list with no one to carry it out. The controller is the worker that turns that list into a live, routing proxy.
